/gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Proteins within a cell respond to a range of signals, and our research is focused on so-called ?redox? regulation of proteins (a contraction of reduction/oxidation). This redox state integrates signals from a cell?s energy levels and the production of free radicals, usually indicative of stress.
Specific amino acids within a protein can be modified in response to these redox signals, which in turn alters the behaviour of the protein: for instance, its activity, its location in the cell, or its interaction with other partner proteins. These redox modifications are readily reversible and can be recycled back to their original, unmodified state by the cell?s natural antioxidants. Therefore, this redox control allows cells to respond rapidly and flexibly to their energy status, stress levels, and environmental cues.
We are using the fruit fly Drosophila as a model system to investigate the importance of redox signalling at a whole organism level. Flies have many advantages in the lab - we can easily control their diet, environment and genetics. Fruit flies share approximately 60 per cent of genes with humans, and this strong evolutionary conservation means that any scientific discoveries from flies are likely to be relevant and applicable to humans.
We are investigating the role of redox signalling in maintaining a healthy metabolism, and whether disruption to normal redox signalling can contribute to the pathology of diseases such as diabetes and to the ageing process.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Redox regulation is emerging as an important modulator of cellular pathways, integrating signals from metabolic status and reactive oxygen species (ROS) production. Redox signalling is mediated by reversible changes in the ratios of redox couples (such as glutathione, thioredoxin, NADPH, NADH), or in the levels of ROS (such as hydrogen peroxide). Target proteins are changed by reversible modification of particular redox-sensitive thiol groups on cysteine residues. These thiol modifications (such as disulphide formation, oxidation, glutathionylation, S-nitrosylation) alter the biological function of the protein (e.g. activity of an enzyme, localisation of a transcription factor, binding interaction with a partner). Critically, redox signalling is distinct from irreversible oxidative damage and operates as a reversible ?redox switch? on a protein, which can be recycled back the basal, reduced thiol state through the action of endogenous antioxidant systems. Therefore, akin to phosphorylation, redox signalling allows the rapid and reversible regulation of target pathways in response to metabolic and environmental cues.
The goals of the group are: firstly, to investigate the importance of redox signalling and metabolism in physiology and pathology; and secondly, to develop novel molecular techniques to assay redox biology in vivo, expanding on our successful design of a mass spec probe approach to quantify hydrogen peroxide levels in vivo. We use the fruit fly Drosophila melanogaster as a model organism, which has many advantages including the availability of powerful genetic tools and the strong evolutionary conservation to mammals. Flies are an excellent, tractable system to study complex processes in vivo, since we can easily control their nutrition and environment, as well as treat with drugs, either through the diet or by microinjection.
We aim to identify, characterise and manipulate redox-sensitive targets using a combination of biochemical, genetic and proteomic approaches, in order to unravel the physiological and metabolic effects of redox signalling. For instance, using a candidate approach, we are generating knock-in fly lines for predicted redox-responsive targets in which the key redox-active cysteine residue has been substituted to produce a redox-inactive mutant, and then assessing the impact in vivo. In parallel, we are performing an unbiased redox proteomic screen in flies to identify novel redox-reactive targets that are altered with age or in response to stress.
Many interventions can improve health and extend lifespan in model organisms including Drosophila, such as manipulating nutrient-sensing pathways either pharmacologically or genetically. However, the underlying molecular mechanisms are unclear. Therefore we are researching whether altered redox metabolism can explain these longevity benefits, and conversely whether the dysregulation of redox signalling networks contributes to the pathophysiology of diseases such as diabetes and to the ageing process.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2013-11-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>1412902</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Innovation Mixer &quot;Flying towards translation - Insights from Drosophila models of disease and physiology&quot; - Organiser, Chair Person and Speaker (07/07/15)</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>555C2E97-ECFC-4A5F-841B-3EDF2826B2C9</gtr:id><gtr:impact>&amp;quot;Innovation Mixers&amp;quot; are a monthly seminar series between the MRC Clinical Sciences Centre and Imperial College on selected topics, and are conceived as a forum for brainstorming and establishing novel collaborations. The event was attended by a broad range of scientist from our institute and Imperial College, ranging from students to group heads.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56e0f07cd38bf2.15514339</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2015</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Ne